│ "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe core issue remains the same: `instsimplify`      │
│ incorrectly simplifies `fabs(%sel)` to `%sel`, which is only valid if `%sel` is proven  │
│ to be non-negative. The provided example demonstrates a case where `%sel` can be        │
│ negative, leading to a miscompilation.\n\nThe IR:\n```llvm\n%abs1 = call half           │
│ @llvm.fabs.f16(half %x)\n%cmp = fcmp ogt half %abs1, 0xH0000\n%sel = select i1 %cmp,    │
│ half %x, half 0xH0000\n%abs2 = call half @llvm.fabs.f16(half %sel)\nret half            │
│ %abs2\n```\n\nThe simplification `fabs(V) -> V` is performed if `isKnownNonNegative(V)` │
│ returns true. `isKnownNonNegative` is now a wrapper around `computeKnownBits(V,         │
│ ...).isNonNegative()`. Therefore, the bug must be in `computeKnownBits` incorrectly     │
│ determining that the sign bit of `%sel` is always 0.\n\n### 2. Analyzing the Code       │
│ Path\n\n1.  `instsimplify` calls `simplifyFabs`.\n2.  `simplifyFabs` calls              │
│ `isKnownNonNegative(%sel)`.\n3.  `isKnownNonNegative` calls                             │
│ `computeKnownBits(%sel)`.\n4.  `computeKnownBits` for a `select` instruction (like      │
│ `%sel`) is handled in `ValueTracking.cpp`. The relevant case is                         │
│ `Instruction::Select`.\n\nThe logic for `select` in `computeKnownBits` is:\n```cpp\n//  │
│ llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp\ncase Instruction::Select: {\n  auto ComputeForArm  │
│ = [&](Value *Arm, bool Invert) {\n    KnownBits Res(Known.getBitWidth());\n             │
│ computeKnownBits(Arm, DemandedElts, Res, Q, Depth + 1);\n                               │
│ adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm(Res, I->getOperand(0), Arm, Invert, Q, Depth);\n    return  │
│ Res;\n  };\n  // Only known if known in both the LHS and RHS.\n  Known =\n              │
│ ComputeForArm(I->getOperand(1), /*Invert=*/false)\n                                     │
│ .intersectWith(ComputeForArm(I->getOperand(2), /*Invert=*/true));\n                     │
│ break;\n}\n```\nThis code computes the known bits for the true arm (`%x`) and the false │
│ arm (`0.0`), refines them using `adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm`, and then intersects the  │
│ results.\n\n`adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm` calls `fcmpImpliesSignBit` to see if the      │
│ comparison condition implies anything about the sign of one of its operands.\n\n### 3.  │
│ Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe function `fcmpImpliesSignBit` contains the following         │
│ logic:\n\n```cpp\n// In fcmpImpliesSignBit\nstatic std::optional<bool>                  │
│ fcmpImpliesSignBit(const FCmpInst *FC, ...)\n{\n  Value *LHS = FC->getOperand(0);\n     │
│ Value *RHS = FC->getOperand(1);\n\n  // Look through fabs.\n  Value *X;\n  if           │
│ (match(LHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))\n    LHS = X;\n  if (match(RHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))\n │
│ RHS = X;\n\n  // ... logic continues as if comparison was on X ...\n}\n```\n\nThis is   │
│ incorrect. When the condition is `fcmp ogt (fabs %x), 0.0`, this code replaces          │
│ `fabs(%x)` with `%x`, and then analyzes `fcmp ogt %x, 0.0`. It concludes that if this   │
│ condition is true, `%x` must be positive (sign bit is 0). This faulty deduction is then │
│ used to mark `%sel` as non-negative, causing the miscompilation.\n\nThe comparison      │
│ `fabs(X) > 0` is true for any non-zero `X`, positive or negative. It does not imply     │
│ anything about the sign of `X`.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to       │
│ remove the incorrect logic that looks through `fabs` in `fcmpImpliesSignBit`.\n\n*      │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp`\n*   **Lines to remove**: The block     │
│ that pattern-matches and replaces `fabs(X)` with `X`.\n\n```cpp\n// EDIT POINT\n//      │
│ File: llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp\n\n  // Look through fabs.\n  Value *X;\n  if │
│ (match(LHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))\n    LHS = X;\n  if (match(RHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))\n │
│ RHS = X;\n```\nRemoving these lines will prevent `fcmpImpliesSignBit` from making an    │
│ incorrect inference about the sign of `%x`, which will cause `isKnownNonNegative(%sel)` │
│ to correctly return false, thus preventing the miscompilation.\n\n### 5.                │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe root cause is an incorrect assumption in `fcmpImpliesSignBit` where   │
│ it strips `fabs` from a comparison operand, leading to an invalid deduction about the   │
│ operand's sign. Removing this faulty look-through logic corrects the analysis and fixes │
│ the bug."})                                                                             │
