│                                                                                         │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                             │
│                                                                                         │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                         │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                          │
│                                                                                         │
│ The core issue remains the same: `instsimplify` incorrectly simplifies `fabs(%sel)` to  │
│ `%sel`, which is only valid if `%sel` is proven to be non-negative. The provided        │
│ example demonstrates a case where `%sel` can be negative, leading to a miscompilation.  │
│                                                                                         │
│ The IR:                                                                                 │
│ ```llvm                                                                                 │
│ %abs1 = call half @llvm.fabs.f16(half %x)                                               │
│ %cmp = fcmp ogt half %abs1, 0xH0000                                                     │
│ %sel = select i1 %cmp, half %x, half 0xH0000                                            │
│ %abs2 = call half @llvm.fabs.f16(half %sel)                                             │
│ ret half %abs2                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                     │
│                                                                                         │
│ The simplification `fabs(V) -> V` is performed if `isKnownNonNegative(V)` returns true. │
│ `isKnownNonNegative` is now a wrapper around `computeKnownBits(V,                       │
│ ...).isNonNegative()`. Therefore, the bug must be in `computeKnownBits` incorrectly     │
│ determining that the sign bit of `%sel` is always 0.                                    │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 2. Analyzing the Code Path                                                          │
│                                                                                         │
│ 1.  `instsimplify` calls `simplifyFabs`.                                                │
│ 2.  `simplifyFabs` calls `isKnownNonNegative(%sel)`.                                    │
│ 3.  `isKnownNonNegative` calls `computeKnownBits(%sel)`.                                │
│ 4.  `computeKnownBits` for a `select` instruction (like `%sel`) is handled in           │
│ `ValueTracking.cpp`. The relevant case is `Instruction::Select`.                        │
│                                                                                         │
│ The logic for `select` in `computeKnownBits` is:                                        │
│ ```cpp                                                                                  │
│ // llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp                                                  │
│ case Instruction::Select: {                                                             │
│   auto ComputeForArm = [&](Value *Arm, bool Invert) {                                   │
│     KnownBits Res(Known.getBitWidth());                                                 │
│     computeKnownBits(Arm, DemandedElts, Res, Q, Depth + 1);                             │
│     adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm(Res, I->getOperand(0), Arm, Invert, Q, Depth);          │
│     return Res;                                                                         │
│   };                                                                                    │
│   // Only known if known in both the LHS and RHS.                                       │
│   Known =                                                                               │
│       ComputeForArm(I->getOperand(1), /*Invert=*/false)                                 │
│           .intersectWith(ComputeForArm(I->getOperand(2), /*Invert=*/true));             │
│   break;                                                                                │
│ }                                                                                       │
│ ```                                                                                     │
│ This code computes the known bits for the true arm (`%x`) and the false arm (`0.0`),    │
│ refines them using `adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm`, and then intersects the results.      │
│                                                                                         │
│ `adjustKnownBitsForSelectArm` calls `fcmpImpliesSignBit` to see if the comparison       │
│ condition implies anything about the sign of one of its operands.                       │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                              │
│                                                                                         │
│ The function `fcmpImpliesSignBit` contains the following logic:                         │
│                                                                                         │
│ ```cpp                                                                                  │
│ // In fcmpImpliesSignBit                                                                │
│ static std::optional<bool> fcmpImpliesSignBit(const FCmpInst *FC, ...)                  │
│ {                                                                                       │
│   Value *LHS = FC->getOperand(0);                                                       │
│   Value *RHS = FC->getOperand(1);                                                       │
│                                                                                         │
│   // Look through fabs.                                                                 │
│   Value *X;                                                                             │
│   if (match(LHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))                                                   │
│     LHS = X;                                                                            │
│   if (match(RHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))                                                   │
│     RHS = X;                                                                            │
│                                                                                         │
│   // ... logic continues as if comparison was on X ...                                  │
│ }                                                                                       │
│ ```                                                                                     │
│                                                                                         │
│ This is incorrect. When the condition is `fcmp ogt (fabs %x), 0.0`, this code replaces  │
│ `fabs(%x)` with `%x`, and then analyzes `fcmp ogt %x, 0.0`. It concludes that if this   │
│ condition is true, `%x` must be positive (sign bit is 0). This faulty deduction is then │
│ used to mark `%sel` as non-negative, causing the miscompilation.                        │
│                                                                                         │
│ The comparison `fabs(X) > 0` is true for any non-zero `X`, positive or negative. It     │
│ does not imply anything about the sign of `X`.                                          │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                           │
│                                                                                         │
│ The fix is to remove the incorrect logic that looks through `fabs` in                   │
│ `fcmpImpliesSignBit`.                                                                   │
│                                                                                         │
│ *   **File**: `llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp`                                     │
│ *   **Lines to remove**: The block that pattern-matches and replaces `fabs(X)` with     │
│ `X`.                                                                                    │
│                                                                                         │
│ ```cpp                                                                                  │
│ // EDIT POINT                                                                           │
│ // File: llvm/lib/Analysis/ValueTracking.cpp                                            │
│                                                                                         │
│   // Look through fabs.                                                                 │
│   Value *X;                                                                             │
│   if (match(LHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))                                                   │
│     LHS = X;                                                                            │
│   if (match(RHS, m_FAbs(m_Value(X))))                                                   │
│     RHS = X;                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                     │
│ Removing these lines will prevent `fcmpImpliesSignBit` from making an incorrect         │
│ inference about the sign of `%x`, which will cause `isKnownNonNegative(%sel)` to        │
│ correctly return false, thus preventing the miscompilation.                             │
│                                                                                         │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                       │
│                                                                                         │
│ The root cause is an incorrect assumption in `fcmpImpliesSignBit` where it strips       │
│ `fabs` from a comparison operand, leading to an invalid deduction about the operand's   │
│ sign. Removing this faulty look-through logic corrects the analysis and fixes the bug.  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                         │
│                                                                                         │
│ ## Suspected Code Locations ##                                                          │
│                                                                                         │
